Such in fact is generally the character of authors who write before the maturity of their lan- guage: and we may be sure that the affectation of cutting up sentences by the suppression of words . which logically belong to them would be the vice of a later age, and foreign to the spirit of an ancient writer, especially of one who rather studied to copy a still remoter antiquity. We may conclude then that the amputatoe sententie& referred to by Seneca, are the author's peculiar turns of thought, which are studiously abrupt and antithetica13 the verba ante expectatum cadentia are certain harsh and jerking cadences in the composition, which are evidently pre- pared with a view to striking effects.
